Village of Burnby
The Village of Burnby, once a lively center of trade, currently resembles a ghost town.  Except for a few hovels on the outskirts and bonfires that periodically get relit by bandits, there are only booths of craftsmen that lie now in rubble and the remains of a tavern -- stone foundation and collapsed wooden poles.  A large one, forming part of the ridge pole, still seems sturdy and in good repair.
You can go southwest, northwest or southeast.

> take pole

> take pole
You pick it up.  Whoa!  something this heavy had better be worth it.
> southeast

> southeast

Holy Lake
A dense fog settles over the Waters of the Brethren.  You can just make out the shoreline in the distance as it curls northwest toward Burnby village and then gets lost in the fog to the east.  Pine trees and thick bramble form a screen, in front of which you see a charcoal brazier faintly smoking, a leather drum, and stumps arranged in a circle.  No sign of anyone present, though you could swear you heard voices faintly chanting something like "Ma-ta-pa."  Below the screen of brush, the sandy soil slopes down to the shore where you see an old raft.
A tiny glint in the midst of the Lake penetrates the rolling mists.
You can go northwest or down.

> down

> down

Lake shore
On this small strand between the pines and the lapping lake water, you can either go back up to the vista of Holy Lake and its surroundings, or you can get in the raft and take your chances on the waves.
You can go up.
You can see a raft and lake water lapping.

